# Sourcing
Be epistemically conservative: every non-trivial claim needs a source — a citation or first-hand observation — unless it is common sense or axiomatic. Seek counter-evidence, not just support. Source preference, in decreasing order:
1. Docs, wiki, peer-reviewed literature
2. Public source code
3. Stack Overflow, GitHub issues, blog posts
4. Local source code (only if no public equivalent)
5. Trial and error

Cite with named footnotes: `[^label]` inline, definition below the paragraph. If a claim lacks support: when it is Henry's, leave the text and flag inline `[^unsupported_label]`; when it is mine, rewrite to match what I actually found.

# Academic Writing
- Write findings into a note with inline references `[text](url)` at point of use.
- Notes (including logs) are readable prose, not append-only transcripts. Keep only what reflects current understanding; remove outdated or redundant content once resolved. Prefer brief conclusions with citations over raw technical detail.
- Citations: external sources go in footnotes (with optional short note); intra-repo references are inline, e.g. `[AGENTS](AGENTS.md#academic-writing)`.

# Literature Review
When surveying a topic, create `/knowledge/survey_{topic}.md` organized as:

````markdown

# Summary
First, describe the central topic.


# Read List
## {Year}
### label (example attention_is_all_you_need_2017)
Title
Summary (may refer to other items); link to its reading note in `reading/` if one exists.
Outbound links: important keywords and citations.

# To Read List:
keywords and citations
````

Iterate the following steps, stops once per 5 papers and report new finds to the user:
1. Search keywords or follow citations, append to to read list
2. Pick the most promising one in to read list, read it and create a section for it
3. remove the original one from to read list, Update the to read list with its outbound links
